Here's the complete migration from ASP.NET Web Forms to ASP.NET Core 8 MVC, addressing all `Thread.Abort`-related patterns.

## Pattern Analysis

Your code has two patterns that rely on `Thread.Abort` internally:

| Pattern | Location | Issue in .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | `btnExport_Click` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` ‚Äî `Thread.Abort` is gone |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `btnRedirect_Click` | The `true` (endResponse) param called `Thread.Abort` internally |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `btnRedirect_Click` | Never thrown in .NET 8 ‚Äî dead code that hides real bugs |

## Migrated Code ‚Äî ASP.NET Core 8

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // POST /Report/Export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        // Return a FileResult ‚Äî the framework handles Content-Disposition,
        // Content-Type, and flushing. No Response.Clear/Write/End needed.
        var data = GenerateReport();
        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    // POST /Report/Redirect
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAction()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Redirect() returns a 302 result ‚Äî no thread abort,
            // no endResponse parameter. The method returns normally.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No catch (ThreadAbortException) ‚Äî it is never thrown in .NET 8.
        // Catching it would silently swallow real exceptions if the type
        // were ever introduced by a library.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() { /* ... */ }
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

**1. `Response.End()` ‚Üí `return File(...)`**
ASP.NET Core actions return `IActionResult`. The framework writes the response ‚Äî you never call `Response.Write`/`End` directly. `File()` sets the content type and `Content-Disposition` header for you.

**2. `Response.Redirect(url, true)` ‚Üí `return Redirect(url)`**
In Web Forms, `true` meant "abort the thread to stop further processing." In Core, you simply `return` an `IActionResult` ‚Äî execution stops naturally at the `return` statement.

**3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` ‚Üí removed entirely**
This catch block existed only because `Response.Redirect(url, true)` threw `ThreadAbortException` as a side effect. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (never `ThreadAbortException`), so this block is dead code. Worse, if left in, it could mask real bugs.

**4. `User.Identity.IsAuthenticated` ‚Üí null-safe check**
In ASP.NET Core, `User.Identity` can be `null` for unauthenticated requests. The `?.` operator prevents a `NullReferenceException`.

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| Keeping `Response.End()` calls | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime ‚Äî no compile error |
| Keeping `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Dead code; hides logic errors and confuses maintainers |
| Writing to `Response.Body` then returning `IActionResult` | Double-write; the framework throws "response already started" |
| Not returning after `Redirect()` | Unlike Web Forms, `Redirect()` doesn't stop execution ‚Äî you **must** `return` |
| Missing `[HttpPost]` attribute | Without it, GET requests reach these endpoints unexpectedly |
